<Layout title="interview cheat sheet" showHome={false}>

  <div class="view-toggle" role="tablist">
    <button data-view="debug" class="active" type="button">🐛 Debugging</button>
    <button data-view="general" type="button">⚙️ General Coding</button>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════ DEBUG VIEW (default) ════════════════ -->
  <div id="view-debug">
    <p class="quick-bar">
      <a href="#dbg-loop">5-move loop</a>
      <a href="#dbg-pdb">pdb commands</a>
      <a href="#dbg-symptoms">symptom → suspect</a>
      <a href="#dbg-archetypes">bug archetypes</a>
      <a href="#dbg-padding-mask">padding mask</a>
      <a href="#dbg-sorting">sorting</a>
      <a href="#dbg-topics">required topics</a>
      <a href="#dbg-mocks">practice</a>
    </p>

    <div class="section" id="dbg-loop">
      <h2>The 5-move loop (every bug, same loop)</h2>
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Step 0 — get a pdb prompt:</strong><br>
        <code>breakpoint()</code> on the suspect line + <code>python -m unittest test_x</code> → opens in your code, skip move 2<br>
        <code>python -m pdb -m unittest test_x.Class.test</code> → opens in unittest, use move 2</p>
      <ol class="loop">
        <li><strong>Read the traceback.</strong> It names the failing line + the symptom.
          Form a hypothesis: "<code>idx</code> is a tuple → it came from <code>passing_indices</code> → the bug's in there."</li>
        <li><strong><code>b file.py:&lt;first line of that function&gt;</code> then <code>c</code>.</strong>
          Freeze at the start of the suspect function.</li>
        <li><strong><code>cl</code> the breakpoint</strong> → now you have manual control (essential before stepping over a recursive call, or it re-fires).</li>
        <li><strong><code>a</code> and <code>ll</code></strong> — see the inputs and the code. Then
          <strong><code>n</code> down the function</strong>, and after each line <strong><code>p</code> the variable</strong> and check your prediction.</li>
        <li><strong>First mismatch = the bug.</strong> If the mismatching line is a function call,
          <strong><code>s</code> into it</strong> and repeat one level deeper.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="dbg-pdb">
      <h2>pdb — the ten commands that matter</h2>
      <table class="dbg-table">
        <thead><tr><th>cmd</th><th>does</th><th>you reach for it when…</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>l</code> / <code>ll</code></td><td>list 11 lines / the whole function</td><td>"where am I in the code"</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>w</code></td><td>print the call stack</td><td>"how did I get here" — esp. recursion</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>a</code></td><td>print the current function's args</td><td>first thing after a breakpoint hits</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>p</code> / <code>pp</code></td><td>print / pretty-print any expression</td><td>inspect a var — <em>or evaluate a call</em>: <code>p np.sum(x,axis=1)</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>n</code></td><td>run line, <strong>step over</strong> calls</td><td>walk down a function</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>s</code></td><td>run line, <strong>step into</strong> calls</td><td>descend into a suspect function</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>r</code></td><td>run until this function returns — <strong>shows the return value</strong></td><td>"what does this actually return"</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>c</code></td><td>continue to next breakpoint</td><td>skip ahead</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>b file:line</code></td><td>set a breakpoint</td><td>stop exactly where you suspect</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>cl N</code></td><td>clear breakpoint N</td><td>stop it re-firing (loops / recursion)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>u</code> / <code>d</code></td><td>move up / down a stack frame</td><td>inspect the <em>caller's</em> variables</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>3 ways into pdb:</strong>
        <code>python -m pdb -m unittest test_x</code> (start under pdb) ·
        <code>breakpoint()</code> in the code (opens pdb there) ·
        post-mortem after a crash: <code>import pdb; pdb.pm()</code>.</p>
      <a href="#top" class="to-top">↑ top</a>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="dbg-symptoms">
      <h2>Symptom → suspect — the fast-triage table</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--muted); margin: -2px 0 6px; font-size: 0.85rem;">
        the failure message usually <em>is</em> the diagnosis. Learn to read it.</p>
      <table class="dbg-table">
        <thead><tr><th>you see…</th><th>look for…</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>nan</code> / <code>inf</code> in the output</td><td>numerical overflow — <strong>subtract the max before <code>np.exp</code></strong> (stable softmax / log-sum-exp)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>ValueError: could not be broadcast … (2,3) (2,)</code></td><td>shape mismatch — a missing <code>keepdims=True</code>, or need <code>x[:, None]</code> to add an axis</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>ValueError: truth value of an array … is ambiguous</code></td><td>Python <code>and</code>/<code>or</code>/<code>not</code> used on a boolean <em>array</em> — use bitwise <code>&amp;</code>/<code>|</code>/<code>~</code>, with parens: <code>(a&gt;0) &amp; (b&gt;0)</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>'tuple' object has no attribute 'ndim'</code></td><td><code>np.where(cond)</code> / <code>np.nonzero()</code> with one arg returns a <strong>tuple</strong> — index <code>[0]</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>result has the right values in the <strong>wrong places</strong></td><td><code>np.where(cond, a, b)</code> — the two branches are swapped</td></tr>
          <tr><td>a field/attribute holds a value that belongs to a <strong>different field</strong> (no error)</td><td>a <code>NamedTuple</code> (or any constructor) built <strong>positionally</strong> with the args in the wrong order — construct by keyword</td></tr>
          <tr><td>array has right values, <strong>wrong shape</strong></td><td>wrong <code>axis=</code> on <code>sum</code>/<code>min</code>/<code>max</code>, or wrong <code>k=</code> on <code>triu</code>/<code>tril</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>passes <strong>alone</strong>, fails <strong>in the suite</strong></td><td>shared mutable state — mutable default arg, or a class-level <code>[]</code>/<code>{}</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>output length off by exactly 1</td><td>recursion base case (<code>&gt;</code> vs <code>&gt;=</code>) or a loop <code>range()</code> off-by-one</td></tr>
          <tr><td>a recursive function "does nothing" / <strong>nested data is missing</strong> from the output</td><td>the recursive call's <strong>return value is discarded</strong> — need <code>return</code> / <code>.extend(...)</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>KeyError</code></td><td><code>d[k]</code> should be <code>d.get(k, default)</code> — the spec names the default</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>RuntimeError: dictionary changed size during iteration</code> (or a loop skips elements)</td><td>mutating a dict/list <em>while iterating it</em> — iterate a <code>list(...)</code> copy, or build a new container</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>AttributeError: can't set attribute</code></td><td>trying to mutate a <code>NamedTuple</code> — it's immutable; use <code>obj._replace(field=...)</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>a "skip if nan" guard never fires, or a <code>max</code>/<code>sum</code> silently becomes <code>nan</code></td><td><code>nan != nan</code> — test with <code>np.isnan</code>; one <code>nan</code> poisons reductions — use <code>np.nanmax</code>/<code>np.nansum</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>you mutate a "local" array and the original changes too</td><td>a plain <strong>slice is a view</strong> — <code>.copy()</code> it (boolean/fancy indexing already copies)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>a stale value after an update — a getter returns pre-update data</td><td>cross-method stale state — the mutating method forgot to invalidate a cache the getter reads</td></tr>
          <tr><td>every random draw identical / not reproducible</td><td>global <code>np.random</code> instead of an instance <code>RandomState</code>, or re-seeding inside a hot path</td></tr>
          <tr><td>a metric is an integer when it should be fractional</td><td><code>//</code> floor division where <code>/</code> was meant</td></tr>
          <tr><td>a probability array doesn't sum to 1</td><td>missing renormalization <em>or</em> dividing by the wrong denominator — use <code>x / x.sum()</code>, not <code>x / len(x)</code></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <a href="#top" class="to-top">↑ top</a>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="dbg-archetypes">
      <h2>Bug archetypes — recognize on sight</h2>
      <h3>NumPy</h3>
      <Code code={numpyArchetypes} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <h3><code>np.bincount</code> — counting into a fixed-length array</h3>
      <Code code={bincountSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><code>np.bincount</code> needs <strong>non-negative integers</strong> —
        a float <code>ids</code> array raises <code>TypeError</code>, a negative id raises
        <code>ValueError</code>; if you see those at a <code>bincount</code> line, the bug is in
        what <code>encode()</code> returned. With <strong><code>weights=</code></strong> it
        returns a <em>float</em> array (summed weights per bin), not int counts — so a
        <code>dtype</code> assertion can fail (mock-1's <code>empirical_means</code>). Reach for
        <code>minlength=</code> 90% of the time; reach for <code>np.zeros</code> +
        <code>np.add.at</code> when an id might exceed <code>V</code> or you want the length
        guaranteed.</p>
      <h3>Broadcasting — divide rows vs. columns by a vector</h3>
      <p class="dbg-sub">The single most common broadcasting fix. Memorize which one needs the reshape.</p>
      <Code code={broadcastSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <table class="dbg-table">
        <thead><tr><th>goal</th><th>vector length</th><th>vector shape needed</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>divide each <strong>row</strong> by <code>v[i]</code></td><td>= num rows</td><td>must be 2-D <code>(N,1)</code> → <code>v[:, None]</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>divide each <strong>column</strong> by <code>v[j]</code></td><td>= num cols</td><td>1-D <code>(N,)</code> is fine — broadcasts as-is</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Rule:</strong> a vector broadcasts against the matrix's
        <em>trailing</em> axis. Columns already line up <code>(N,)</code>; rows need an explicit
        column shape <code>(N,1)</code>. This is the same fix as <code>keepdims=True</code> after a
        row-wise <code>sum</code> — and exactly the bug in mock-5's <code>normalize_rows</code>.</p>
      <h3>The two modes of <code>np.where</code></h3>
      <Code code={whereSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>3-arg = replace, 1-arg = locate.</strong>
        <code>np.where(cond, x, y)</code> is a vectorized if-else — same shape out, each
        element picked from <code>x</code> or <code>y</code>. <code>np.where(cond)</code> is
        just <code>np.nonzero</code> — a <em>tuple</em> of index arrays; index <code>[0]</code>
        for the 1-D case. Mixing up the two modes (or forgetting the <code>[0]</code>) is one
        of the most common NumPy bugs — it's in mock-2 and mock-6.</p>
      <h3>The two meanings of <code>None</code> in NumPy</h3>
      <Code code={noneSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Don't confuse them:</strong> <code>axis=None</code>
        <em>removes</em> dimensions (reduce over the flattened array); <code>x[..., None]</code>
        <em>adds</em> one. The index form is your broadcasting tool — it's how you turn a
        <code>(N,)</code> vector into the <code>(N,1)</code> column from the rule above.</p>
      <h3 id="dbg-padding-mask">Padding mask on <code>scores</code> (mock-5 attention)</h3>
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Spec:</strong> <code>scores</code> shape <code>(batch, seq, seq)</code>
        with <code>scores[b, i, j]</code> = logit for <strong>query</strong> <code>i</code> attending to
        <strong>key</strong> <code>j</code>. <code>pad_mask</code> shape <code>(batch, seq)</code>:
        <code>True</code> = real token, <code>False</code> = padding. A padding <strong>key</strong> at
        position <code>j</code> must become <code>-np.inf</code> for <strong>every</strong> query
        <code>i</code> — i.e. blank the whole <strong>key column</strong> <code>j</code> in
        <code>scores[b, :, j]</code>.</p>
      <Code code={paddingMaskAttentionSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p><strong>Raw numbers — batch 0 only</strong> (<code>pad_mask[0] = [True, True, False]</code>,
        all <code>scores[0, :, :]</code> start as <code>1.0</code>):</p>
      <table class="dbg-table">
        <thead><tr><th></th><th>key 0</th><th>key 1</th><th>key 2 (padding)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>wanted <code>scores[0]</code></th><td>1</td><td>1</td><td><code>-inf</code> for queries 0,1,2</td></tr>
          <tr><th>buggy output</th><td>1</td><td>1</td><td><code>1, 1, -inf</code> — only query 2 masked</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="dbg-sub">The test asserts <code>np.all(out[0, :, 2] == -np.inf)</code> i.e.
        <code>out[0, 0, 2]</code>, <code>out[0, 1, 2]</code>, <code>out[0, 2, 2]</code> must all be
        <code>-inf</code>. With <code>pad_mask[:, :, None]</code>, cell <code>scores[0, i, 2]</code> uses
        <code>np.where(pad_mask[0, i], …)</code> — so queries <code>0</code> and <code>1</code> read
        <code>pad_mask[0, 0]</code> and <code>pad_mask[0, 1]</code> (both <code>True</code>) and
        <strong>keep</strong> <code>1.0</code> at key column 2. Only query <code>2</code> reads
        <code>pad_mask[0, 2] == False</code> and gets <code>-inf</code>.</p>
      <table class="dbg-table">
        <thead><tr><th></th><th>what went wrong</th><th>fix</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Bug</th><td><code>np.where(pad_mask[:, :, None], scores, -np.inf)</code></td><td>condition tied to <strong>query</strong> index <code>i</code></td></tr>
          <tr><th>Cause</th><td colspan="2">Singleton axis is last → <code>pad_mask[b, i]</code> is copied across all keys <code>j</code> — masks by row (query), not by column (key).</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Fix</th><td><code>np.where(pad_mask[:, None, :], scores, -np.inf)</code></td><td>singleton on <strong>query</strong> axis → <code>pad_mask[b, j]</code> applies to every <code>i</code></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <h3>Pure Python</h3>
      <Code code={pythonArchetypes} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <h3>Recursion</h3>
      <Code code={recursionSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Two failure shapes:</strong> a recursive function that
        "does nothing" / drops nested data → its recursive call's <em>return value is
        discarded</em> (need <code>return</code> or <code>.extend(...)</code>). An output
        whose length is off by exactly 1 → a <em>base-case</em> <code>&gt;</code> vs
        <code>&gt;=</code> (or a loop-<code>range()</code>) off-by-one. <code>pdb</code>:
        <code>w</code> shows the call stack; <code>cl</code> the breakpoint before stepping
        over a recursive call or it re-fires on every level.</p>
      <h3>Slices clamp — never <code>IndexError</code></h3>
      <Code code={slicingSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <h3><code>NamedTuple</code> — positional construction silently swaps fields</h3>
      <Code code={namedtupleSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Tell:</strong> a field/attribute holds a value that obviously
        belongs to a <em>different</em> field, with no error raised — the constructor was
        called positionally with the args in the wrong order. <strong>Fix &amp; habit:</strong>
        construct NamedTuples by keyword. NamedTuple gives you no positional-arg safety —
        same-typed fields swap silently.</p>
      <h3>Mutable default arguments</h3>
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Rule:</strong> a default value is bound <em>once</em>, at
        <code>def</code> time. A mutable default (<code>[]</code>, <code>{}</code>,
        <code>set()</code>) is <em>one shared object</em> across every call — mutate it and
        state leaks between calls (and earlier return values change under you, since they're
        the same object).</p>
      <Code code={mutableDefaultSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><strong>Tell:</strong> a test that passes alone but fails in the suite,
        or a function whose output grows across calls (mock-2's <code>merge_vocabs</code>).
        <strong>One-liner memory:</strong> <em>default <code>None</code>, build <code>[]</code>
        inside the function body.</em></p>
      <h3>OOV tokens — safe dict lookup in <code>encode()</code></h3>
      <Code code={oovSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub">After merges, tokens are still <em>strings</em> — one never seen in
        the vocab <code>KeyError</code>s on <code>d[tok]</code>. The spec names the default
        (<code>unk_id</code>). mock-2 / mock-4 <code>encode()</code>.</p>
      <h3>BPE / tokenizer — what to check</h3>
      <ul class="tight">
        <li><strong>Vocab layout:</strong> specials first (id 0, 1), then learned tokens —
          <code>vocab_size</code> is the TOTAL, so slice learned tokens with
          <code>vocab_size - num_special</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Special ids:</strong> <code>unk_id</code> / <code>pad_id</code> are
          same-typed ints — trivially swapped in positional construction (build by keyword).</li>
        <li><strong>Merge loop:</strong> re-scan from the start after each merge, and cover
          the LAST adjacent pair — <code>range(len-1)</code>, not <code>len-2</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>encode:</strong> merged tokens are strings —
          <code>token_to_id.get(tok, unk_id)</code>, never <code>[tok]</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Counts:</strong> <code>np.bincount(ids, minlength=vocab_size)</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Ratios:</strong> chars-per-token is a float — <code>/</code>, not <code>//</code>.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Floats &amp; NaN — <code>log(0)</code>, <code>nan != nan</code>, <code>==</code></h3>
      <Code code={floatNanSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><code>log(0)</code> is <code>-inf</code>, <code>log(negative)</code> is
        <code>nan</code> — and one <code>nan</code> poisons every <code>max</code>/<code>sum</code>/
        <code>mean</code> downstream. <code>nan</code> also compares <em>unequal to everything,
        including itself</em>, so a <code>if x == x</code> / "skip if nan" guard silently never
        fires — use <code>np.isnan</code>. Never <code>==</code> floats; use
        <code>math.isclose</code> / <code>np.isclose</code>.</p>
      <h3>View vs. copy — slices alias, fancy-indexing copies</h3>
      <Code code={viewCopySnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub">A plain <strong>slice is a view</strong> — mutating it mutates the
        original (the NumPy version of mock-7's list-aliasing bug). <strong>Boolean / fancy
        indexing returns a copy.</strong> The inconsistency is the trap: <code>.copy()</code>
        when you need an array you can mutate freely.</p>
      <h3><code>np.max</code> vs <code>np.maximum</code> — reduction vs. elementwise</h3>
      <Code code={maxMaximumSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><code>np.max(a)</code> <em>reduces</em> to a scalar;
        <code>np.maximum(a, b)</code> is <em>elementwise</em> and the go-to for clamping/flooring
        an array. Mixing them gives a <code>TypeError</code> (the second arg is read as
        <code>axis</code>) or a scalar where you wanted an array. Same trap:
        <code>np.min</code>/<code>np.minimum</code>, <code>np.sum</code>/<code>np.add</code>.</p>
      <a href="#top" class="to-top">↑ top</a>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="dbg-sorting">
      <h2>Quick reference — sorting</h2>
      <Code code={sortingSnippet} lang="python" theme="github-light" wrap />
      <p class="dbg-sub"><code>sorted()</code> returns a <em>new</em> list; <code>.sort()</code>
        mutates in place and returns <code>None</code> (a classic bug — <code>xs = xs.sort()</code>
        leaves you with <code>None</code>). <code>key=</code> maps each element to the value you
        sort <em>by</em>. To sort <strong>descending by a numeric key</strong>, negate it:
        <code>key=lambda i: -counts[i]</code>. For <strong>tie-breaking</strong>, return a tuple —
        it compares left-to-right, so <code>(group, -score)</code> is "group ascending, then score
        descending."</p>
      <a href="#top" class="to-top">↑ top</a>
    </div>

